<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> My LOTR TCG Experience<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.64)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12699'>Magee "Lalaithien" Page</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12699&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 9, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Right off the bat, this is not an article about strategy or deck designing or anything of the sort.  That much said, I would suggest  to those of you who do not wish to read anything besides that to stop reading this immediately. I doubt you will hold any interest in it. So, if you do decide to read this, then I thank you for having an open mind.<br>
<br>
Basically I&#39;m writing this because I really like to write. Yes, you would know that if you&#39;ve visited my page. Anyway, this is an article about my experience in the card gaming world thus far. Starting from the very beginning.<br>
<br>
As you may already know (from reading my page), my dad has exposed trading card games to me since I was four. It was more a matter of me interested in it actually, rather than him introducing it to me. He started playing them so I immediately thought it would be fun. I really look up to my dad, and I consider him one of the few people in my life who I am influenced by. Moving on, I started playing when I was eight.<br>
<br>
With that said already, I will move onto my experiences in the LOTR TCG. The rest before that isn&#39;t all that interesting. However, I should mention that with all my experiences with card games I have always been the odd girl out.  Usually the youngest also. That doesn&#39;t sound like it would be a superlative fact in this article, but it is actually why I was most inclined to write this. The majority of you do not know how it&#39;s like to be the one of the very few girls interested in things such as card games or Tolkien. I know there are some females out there, but I mean a girl. As in a minor. It seems somewhat of a frivolous comment but it has such an impact on certain people. I mean think about, can you imagine an eight year old girl competing in a TCG tournament? I admit that it was awkward to be that girl, however that&#39;s the con of being the &quot;smart one.&quot; <br>
<br>
Ok, seriously moving on... The very first time I played the LOTR TCG. It was earlier this year (in February) when I picked it up with my dad, and we did so because we are very big fans of LOTR in general. We had somewhat &#39;quit&#39; on trading card games for awhile but since this was LOTR related we said we&#39;d give it a shot. I immediately fell in love with it, and I couldn&#39;t wait to introduce it to a very good friend of mine, Danielle. (She is also a very big LOTR fan!) <br>
<br>
Unlike me, Danielle has never played a TCG before, but she picked this up automatically being the bright kid that she is. =D (BTW, she is only a year older than I am.) I taught her how to play in an airport waiting for a flight to Wisconsin for our school&#39;s annual basketball tournaments (in March). I remember when Danielle was first looking through all the cards I had, a fellow team mates younger sister came to join us. She picked up a stack of cards flipped through them commenting that all the orcs were ugly. She eventually noticed a Pathfinder which has a picture of Legolas and Aragorn on it, she pointed at Legolas and said &quot;Ooo, she&#39;s pretty!&quot; HAHA! Anyway, so I taught Danielle how to play at the airport, of course I was also still new to the game so I taught her quite a bit of mistakes. (Example: you can heal all your wounds at a sanctuary. How helpful that would be if it were true.) All throughout the trip, Danielle and I would do nothing but play. On the airplane in the hotel rooms, in between basketball games, as much as possible. So you can imagine how life is like is now...<br>
<br>
My very first tournament...<br>
Being so into the game, it would be typical of me to want to play with different people. That&#39;s when my dad took us to WonderCon for a sealed deck tournament in Oakland (in April? I think). (I begged for Danielle to come along = ] ) It was sealed deck for the Mines of Moria expansion. (I wore a shirt that said &quot;Can&#39;t sleep, Balrog will eat me.&quot; Heh...) I actually didn&#39;t do too poorly, surprisingly because I was the youngest there- yet again. I received a Gandalf starter and boosters from MoM and the Premiere set. I won my first game against Blake Someone???, lost to Alfred Dong (imagine that = D) in my second game, won against someone else I can&#39;t remember, and lost my last game to this lady, I&#39;m sorry I can&#39;t remember anyone&#39;s names! In the end I received 5th place, Danielle got 4th!, and my dad got 7th place. It was very fun and a really encouraging experience for my first LOTR TCG tournament. Plus I got an awesome Pippin foil for participation!<br>
<br>
I continued to play, getting better than my dad! During summer we all participated in another sealed deck tournament.<br>
<br>
My second tournament...<br>
Sealed deck in July, the realease for Realms of the Elf Lords. I did incredibly worse in this tournament than my first one, but that is blamed on the useless pulls I got from the boosters. I didn&#39;t even get the common Balrog! Oh well... I remember winning my first game against somebody, lost to Philip Green (heh), and then I can&#39;t remember the rest! (Apologies again to forgotten people, you may have noticed I have the worst memory ever!) Maybe I don&#39;t want to remember the rest... However I did get 7th place, Danielle got 8th!, and Dad got 5th! <br>
<br>
After that we all took a little break from tournament life. We improved our decks and improved our skills. We would soon compete in CONSTRUCTED deck... Unfortunately,  no Danielle here. She moved to Wisconsin for high school, while I&#39;m still stuck in the superficial torment of eighth grade... ugh...<br>
<br>
My first constructed deck tournament... <br>
Now, I don&#39;t remember much at all here but I do remember that I took 4th place and only lost my last game against Alfred (yet again!). I was actually really happy about my accomplishment!<br>
<br>
Following (constructed) tournaments...<br>
I guess to simply state it, ever since that first constructed tournament, it all went down hill from there... I have progressed and become utterly bad at this game! Well, maybe not too awful but worse than before. <br>
<br>
Anyway, hopefully I didn&#39;t waste too much of your time. Then again, you weren&#39;t obligated to read this! At least for those of you that know me, now you know me even more! Haha, how logical... Basically, now you know my LOTR TCG experience. (If that was at all relevant.) I guess, if you really had nothing to do, you could compare this to your experience and see how they contrast due to certain circumstances. Oh, my rating is a whoppin&#39; 1605! HAHA! I die laughing... Alright, I&#39;ll stop there and spare you of all other boring details! I&#39;m looking forward to hear from at least someone! Heh, that&#39;s all folks!  <br>
<br>
P.S. Smiley faces awarded to all the people I&#39;ve met since the first time I&#39;ve played in a tournament, a gold star to my dad for exposing me to cards, and a big &quot;hat&quot; hug to Danielle! (If you don&#39;t the joke, be thankful that you don&#39;t!) Reminder: be nice to the newbies! It really means a lot, and good deeds are their own reward! =D<br>
